**Step 1 – Compute the total distance**

\[
\text{Distance}_\text{total}=60\;\text{km}+40\;\text{km}=100\;\text{km}
\]

---

**Step 2 – Compute the time for each leg**

\[
\text{Time}_1=\frac{\text{Distance}_1}{\text{Speed}_1}
            =\frac{60\;\text{km}}{30\;\text{km/h}}
            =2\;\text{h}
\]

\[
\text{Time}_2=\frac{\text{Distance}_2}{\text{Speed}_2}
            =\frac{40\;\text{km}}{20\;\text{km/h}}
            =2\;\text{h}
\]

---

**Step 3 – Compute the total time**

\[
\text{Time}_\text{total}= \text{Time}_1+\text{Time}_2
                        = 2\;\text{h}+2\;\text{h}=4\;\text{h}
\]

---

**Step 4 – Compute the average speed**

Average speed is defined as total distance divided by total time:

\[
\boxed{\text{Average speed}= \frac{\text{Distance}_\text{total}}{\text{Time}_\text{total}}
       = \frac{100\;\text{km}}{4\;\text{h}}
       = 25\;\text{km/h}}
\]

So the car’s average speed over the whole 100‑km trip is **25 km/h**.
